Looking at your code, I can see the issue - in the updateTable() function, you're limiting the display to only the first 100 species with .slice(0, 100). This is an easy fix! You just need to remove that slice.

Here's the modified updateTable() function (around line 200-210 in your JavaScript). Replace the entire function with this:

```javascript
function updateTable() {
    const searchTerm = document.getElementById('searchInput').value.toLowerCase();
    const tableBody = document.getElementById('tableBody');
    
    let displayData = filteredData;
    if (searchTerm) {
        displayData = filteredData.filter(row => 
            (row.scientific_name && row.scientific_name.toLowerCase().includes(searchTerm)) ||
            (row.common_name && row.common_name.toLowerCase().includes(searchTerm))
        );
    }
    
    tableBody.innerHTML = '';
    displayData.forEach(row => {  // Removed the .slice(0, 100) here
        const tr = document.createElement('tr');
        
        // Format months as abbreviated lists
        const flowerMonths = getActiveMonths(row, 'flower');
        const seedMonths = getActiveMonths(row, 'seed');
        
        tr.innerHTML = `
            <td><i>${row.scientific_name || ''}</i></td>
            <td>${row.common_name || '-'}</td>
            <td>${row.family || '-'}</td>
            <td>${row.state || 'Australia'}</td>
            <td class="month-cell">${formatMonths(flowerMonths)}</td>
            <td class="month-cell">${formatMonths(seedMonths)}</td>
        `;
        tableBody.appendChild(tr);
    });
    
    if (displayData.length === 0) {
        tableBody.innerHTML = '<tr><td colspan="6">No species match your filters</td></tr>';
    }
    
    // Update the result count text to show all results
    document.getElementById('resultCount').textContent = 
        `${displayData.length} species`;  // Removed the "showing first 100" part
}
```

The key changes are:

1. Removed .slice(0, 100) from the displayData.forEach loop so it now shows ALL filtered species
2. Updated the result count text to simply show the total number of species without the "showing first 100" note

That's it! Your app will now show all filtered results, and users can scroll through them using the existing scrollable table container (which already has max-height: 500px and overflow-y: auto in your CSS).

The rest of your app will work exactly as before - filters, charts, search, and sorting will all continue to function normally with the complete dataset.
